Builder Design Pattern:
    "Construct a complex object step-by-step, and only build it when you're ready."
    Core idea: Separate the construction of a complex object from its representation.

Why Do We Need It?

Problem Without Builder
    - Telescoping constructors (too many params)
    - Can't create partially configured objects
    - Object mutable after creation
    - Hard to read new User("John",null,0,true,null)
    - No validation before object creation
Solution With Builder
    + Fluent step-by-step construction
    + Optional fields handled cleanly
    + Immutable object after build()
    + Readable User.builder().name("John").active(true).build()
    + Validate in build() before returning


When To Use Builder?
    4+ constructor parameters
    Many optional fields
    Immutable objects needed
    Object needs validation before use
    Same construction, different representations

*** Avoid when: Object has 1-2 fields — builder adds unnecessary boilerplate.


Build in Builders in Java
-------------------------
// StringBuilder — classic builder
String result = new StringBuilder()
        .append("Hello")
        .append(", ")
        .append("World")
        .toString();

// ProcessBuilder
Process process = new ProcessBuilder("java", "-version")
        .directory(new File("/usr/local"))
        .redirectErrorStream(true)
        .start();

// Stream.Builder
Stream<String> stream = Stream.<String>builder()
        .add("a").add("b").add("c")
        .build();

// URI Builder (Java 11+)
URI uri = URI.create("https://api.example.com/users");

Built-in Builders in Spring Boot
--------------------------------
UriComponentsBuilder
MockMvcRequestBuilders
WebClient
ResponseEntity
Mockito


@Getter
@Builder(builderClassName = "OrderBuilder", buildMethodName = "create")
@ToString
public class Order {

    @NonNull private final String orderId;
    @NonNull private final String customerId;
    @NonNull private final String productId;
    private final int quantity;
    private final double price;
    @NonNull private final String shippingAddress;
    @NonNull private final String paymentType;
    @Builder.Default private final String couponCode  = "";
    @Builder.Default private final boolean isGift     = false;
    @Builder.Default private final String giftMessage = "";

    // Extend Lombok builder to add validation
    public static class OrderBuilder {

        public Order create() {
            // Pre-build validation
            validateRequiredFields();
            validateBusinessRules();
            return new Order(orderId, customerId, productId, quantity,
                             price, shippingAddress, paymentType,
                             couponCode, isGift, giftMessage);
        }

        private void validateRequiredFields() {
            if (price <= 0)
                throw new IllegalArgumentException("Price must be positive");
            if (quantity <= 0)
                throw new IllegalArgumentException("Quantity must be positive");
        }

        private void validateBusinessRules() {
            if (isGift && (giftMessage == null || giftMessage.isBlank()))
                throw new IllegalArgumentException("Gift message required for gift orders");
        }
    }
}

// Spring Service using builder
@Service
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class OrderService {

    private final OrderRepository orderRepository;

    public Order createOrder(OrderRequest request) {
        Order order = Order.builder()
                .orderId(UUID.randomUUID().toString())
                .customerId(request.getCustomerId())
                .productId(request.getProductId())
                .quantity(request.getQuantity())
                .price(request.getPrice())
                .shippingAddress(request.getShippingAddress())
                .paymentType(request.getPaymentType())
                .couponCode(request.getCouponCode())
                .isGift(request.isGift())
                .giftMessage(request.getGiftMessage())
                .create();  // validates before returning

        return orderRepository.save(order);
    }
}


